Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling. A mousselike drilling disturbance occurs in the first 5 cm of Section 1.

Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling. As with the surrounding intervals, mottling is generally cm to decimeter scale. Section 2 contains one long brown mottle (20YR 4/2) from 28-45 cm.

Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling. A secondary browner color (5GY 4/1) dominants from 0-35 cm and is a nannofossil diatom ooze with radiolarians.  As with the surrounding intervals, mottling is generally cm to decimeter scale, with a notable oxide layer at 48-50 cm.

Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling.  Although the Munsell color of Section 4 matches that of the preceding Sections, it appears slightly browner and grades from more brown (5GY 4/1) at the top to more greenish (5GY 5/1) at the bottom. The darker interval is a nannofossil diatom ooze with radiolarians.

Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling.  As with Section 4, Section 5 appears slightly browner at the top and grades from 5GY 4/1 (from approximately 0-60 cm) to more greenish (5GY 5/1) at the bottom. The darker interval is a nannofossil diatom ooze with radiolarians.  A larger oxide patch occurs at 118 to 120 cm.

Section 6 is primarily a nannofossil diatom ooze with radiolarians and ranges from 5GY 4/1 (greenish gray) to darker greenish grey (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling. Section 6 is predominately the browner color (5GY 4/1) although a secondary, bluer color (10GY 5/1) dominants from 66-100 cm. A small tan spot occurs from 55-56 cm.

Section 7 is a diatom ooze with clay and is a lighter blue (10GY 5/1) than the preceding sections, particularly from 0-51cm.  From 51-87 cm, the mottling of large brown (10Y 4/1) burrows are common. A core liner disturbance (collapsed sediment) disturbs the Section from 57 to 87 cm.
Diatom ooze with clay is 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray) with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 3/1) mottling.

Section 1 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. Coring disturbance disrupts the early interval of Section 1, with likely fall-in from 0-30 cm, a large (6 cm in diameter) Mn-nodule from 24-30 cm, and cracked sediment from 48-50cm.

Section 2 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. In contrast to Core 11, brown mottling (rather than darker, oxide mottles) is dominant in Core 12.  A secondary, browner color (10Y 4/1) dominates from 125-150 cm. This brown interval continues through the top of Section 3 and is notably characterized by fine, light blue-grey Chondrites burrows.  The brown interval is only slightly bioturbated in contrast moderate bioturbation in the rest of the section.

Overall, Section 3 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. This section has three main intervals based on color and bioturbation.  The brown interval (10Y 4/1) with fine Chondrites burrows (i.e., slight bioturbation) of end-Section 2 continues in Section 3 to 18 cm.  A gradational contact occurs from 18-32cm. The second interval (80-114cm) is heavily bioturbated, markedly bluer (5G 5/1), and contains patches with ?chlorite and white flecks of silt sized quartz at approximately 74-84 cm. The third color interval is greenish gray (5GY 5/1) and is similar to the mottling (moderate bioturbation) and colors dominating in Section 2.

Section 4 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. The color change begun in Section 3 (Section 3, 114-150cm) continues and darkens in Section 4 as the secondary, browner color (10Y 4/1).  The browner interval spans from 0 to 28 cm and is replaced by a moderately bioturbated, mottled, greenish gray (5GY 5/1) like those in Section 2.

Section 5 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. Mottling is less pronounced and more layered (centimeter scaled) in Section 5 as compared to previous intervals. A particular concentrated oxide layer occurs from 20-24cm.

Section 6 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling. Mottling is less pronounced as compared to early sections in the core. A green layer (?chlorite) occurs from 51-53 cm.
Section 7 is a greenish gray (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling.
The CC is a greenish grey (5GY 5/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling.
Section 1 is a browner greenish gray (10Y 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and bluer (5GY 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation.

Section 2 is a browner greenish gray (10Y 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and bluer (5GY 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation. A secondary background color of bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) is present from 104-105 cm.

Section 3 is a browner greenish gray (10Y 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and bluer (5GY 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation. A secondary background color of bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) is present from 102-150 cm.

Section 4 is a bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation. Abundant brown
mottling occurs from 0-72 cm and a browner greenish grey (10Y 4/1) appears to begin at 144 cm.

Section 5 is a browner greenish gray (10Y 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and bluer (5GY 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation. A secondary background color of bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) is present from 20-65 cm and 72-79 cm, with a gradational increase to brown from 79-150 cm.

Section 6 is a bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation.  A browner interval characterizes the first 0-50 cm with a gradational contact from 50-85 cm with blue. A distinctly green patch of ?chlorite occurs from 91-93 cm.
Section 7 is a bluer greenish gray (5GY 4/1) clay with darker (up to 5GY 3/1) and browner (10Y 4/1) mottling from moderate bioturbation.

Section 1 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay than in preceding cores (e.g, Cores 10-13), with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation. A notable thick (36-40 cm) green layer of possible chlorite occurs in Section 1, and darker possible disseminated sulfide layers from 12-16 and 31-34 cm.

Section 2 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation.  Browner greenish grey  (10Y 4/1) clay layers occur from 0-5, 12-41, 64-89 cm.

Section 3 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation, but is generally darker than preceding intervals due to increased brown mottling. The section becomes browner from 126-150 cm.

Section 4 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation. A lighter blue interval (5GY 4/1) with sulfide mottling occurs from 66-74 cm (with particularly thick sulfides from 71-78 cm). This bluer interval appears similar to a later interval identified as clay with diatoms.  From 89 to 109 cm is a relatively dense interval of ?chlorite mottling.

Section 5 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay than in preceding cores (e.g, Cores 10-13), with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation. From 0-121 cm sediments appear darker than the interval that follows.

Section 6 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation. A lighter blue interval (5GY 4/1) with sulfide mottling occurs from 78-100 cm and is identified as clay with diatoms.

Section 7 is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1) clay than in preceding cores (e.g, Cores 10-13), with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation. Decimeter-scale variation between ligher greenish grey and browner greenish grey occur.
The CC is a lighter greenish gray (10GY 5/1), with brown (10Y 4/1), green (5G 4/1) and darker (up to 5GY 3/1) mottling due to moderate bioturbation.
Biosiliceous clay with nannofossils. The color is  5GY 4/1 (dark greenish gray) and 5GY 5/1 (greenish gray).  The burrowing intensity is moderate.

Mottled with darker to browner mottles (up to 5GY 4/1).  The Munsell color indicated (10Y 5/1), the browner greenish grey background color in Core 22, is the dominant color (0-95 cm).  A secondary color, bluer greenish grey (5GY 5/1) dominates from 95-150 cm.

Mottled and layered with darker to browner mottles (up to 5GY 4/1). A secondary, browner greenish grey color (10Y 5/1, clay with nannofossils) dominates from 96-107 cm and is followed by a greyer layer (107-110 cm), a blue layer with darker flecks (110-112 cm), and an unmottled bluer greenish grey interval (112-150 cm).
Heavy mottling imparts the browner greenish grey color of Section 4.

The coloration and mottling of Section 5 is like that observed in Section 4 up to 110 cm. A secondary browner greenish grey (10Y 5/1, clay with nannofossils)  dominates from 115-121 cm  and is followed by a greyer layer (121-122) and a relatively unmottled, bluer greenish grey interval from 122-131 cm. Section 5, 131-150 cm begins a relatively sparsely mottled interval which carries through to the end of the Core (i.e., through Section 6,7, and CC).
Relatively fewer brown mottles (as is observed at the end of Section 5).
Relatively fewer brown mottles (as is observed at the end of Section 5 and through Section 6). An unmottled, heavily to completely bioturbated interval occurs from 31 to 69 cm.
Relatively fewer brown mottles (as is observed at the end of Section 5 and through Section 6 an 7). Darker mottling resumes at 19 cm in the CC.

Section 1 is predominately a heavily mottled and layered browner greenish grey (10Y 5/1) clay (0-21 cm and 58-93 cm). A slightly bluer, less mottled interval (21-58 cm) and an interval characterized by centimeter scale ?sulfide layering (111-150 cm) occur. Bioturbation ranges from moderate to complete, and notably includes Zoophycus burrows. The darkest (10Y 4/1), broadest ?sulfide layers occur between 118 and 123 cm.

Section 2 is predominately a heavily mottled and layered browner greenish grey (10Y 5/1) clay (0-21 cm and 58-93 cm). The degree of mottling and layer (attributed to bioturbation of sulfides) varies throughout with moderate density of mottling and layering from 0-21 and 129-150 cm and heavy brown (5GY 5/1) mottling from 40-122.  A green, ?glaconite nodule occurs from 23-26 cm (during a interval of relatively heavy bioturbation), followed by a green horizon at 53-56 cm, mm-scale green layers are also found from 0-21 cm. A pronounced brown layer is situated at 120-129 cm.
Indistinct mm to cm scale mottling and layering throughout.
